	<span id="content"></span>
	<main>
		<img width="1750" height="841" src="https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/header-feral-pigs-in-hawaii.jpg" class="singlepostthumb wp-post-image" alt="feral pig in Hawaii" decoding="async" fetchpriority="high" srcset="https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/header-feral-pigs-in-hawaii.jpg 1750w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/header-feral-pigs-in-hawaii-520x250.jpg 520w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/header-feral-pigs-in-hawaii-1200x577.jpg 1200w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/header-feral-pigs-in-hawaii-768x369.jpg 768w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/header-feral-pigs-in-hawaii-1536x738.jpg 1536w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/header-feral-pigs-in-hawaii-900x433.jpg 900w" sizes="(max-width: 1750px) 100vw, 1750px" /><div class="post-thumbnail-caption">The Polynesian people first brought domesticated pigs to Hawai‘i over 1,000 years ago and maintained them in captivity. Conflict and social changes brought on by colonization and the privatization of land in the 19th and 20th centuries eventually forced Hawaiians to abandon their livestock, allowing them to go feral. Photo by Lucy Pemoni/AP Photo</div>
			<article class="main container col4">
								<header class="maincol">
										<h1 class="pagetitle">Islands of the Feral Pigs</h1>
										<h2 class="dek singlepagecontainer">In Hawai‘i, people, pigs, and ecosystems only have so much room to coexist, and the pigs exist a little too much.</h2>
										<section class="singlebyline singlepagecontainer">
						<h3 class="invis">Authored by</h3>
						by  
										<a href="https://hakaimagazine.com/profiles/brendan-borrell/" class="tagmanager" id="author_link_top" >Brendan Borrell</a>								<br/>
												</section>
					 
					<aside class="singlebydatewords singlepagecontainer">
						<h3 class="invis">Wordcount</h3>
						October 31, 2024 | 4,800 words, about 24 minutes
					</aside>

					
				</header>

				
